EASY APRICOT EASTER HAM 
from Chef Lisa at Global Gardens
PRO TIP: use ANY fruit balsamic from Global Gardens!
One bone in ham about 4-6 lbs
1/4 Cup  GG apricot balsamic vinegar
Two tablespoons honey
1 tbsp Global Gardens olive oil (any! 💚)
1 T cornstarch 
1 T Global Gardens Counterfeit Caviar aka Mustard Seed Spread
1 sprig of rosemary, destemmed, minced
1/2t ground black pepper

Preheat oven to 425°
Place ham in roasting pan just large enough to hold it snugly. With a sharp knife, Pierce the ham several times at least 2 in deep.

In a small bowl, combine Apricot Balsamic, honey, olive oil, cornstarch, and mustard, mixing into a paste.  Spoon mixture over ham, sprinkling rosemary and pepper over top. Bake, uncovered, for 10 minutes to seal in the juices and create a crust. Turn oven temp to 325° roasting an additional 45 minutes until internal temperature is 165°. Remove ham from oven, basting with its cooking juices. Let Ham sit for 10 minutes before slicing. #happyeaster🐰 #easterrecipes #hamrecipe #balsamic # easyrecipe

What to do with leftover Easter ham? Well, first, make sure you buy a bone-in ham. If you’re a meat eater, you know that bones make it all taste better… Think boneless, skinless chicken breasts…ew. Just go for the bones!

Chef Lisa’s Easter Ham Comfort Soup

Ingredients:
1/3 cup Global Gardens Greek Koroneiki EVOO
Any large pieces of fat carved from leftover meat/ham
1 onion finely chopped
1 cup large carrot peeled, diced
1/2 cup diced celery
3 cups peeled and diced Yukon Gold potatoes
1 1/2 Cup cooked ham 
2-3 Roma diced tomatoes 
4 cloves garlic minced 
1/3 cup all-purpose flour
2 cups chicken stock or broth
3 cups whole or 2% milk (can use plain oat milk for dairy free)
Fresh cracked black pepper
Salt to taste
1/4 cup GG Meyer lemon vinegar

Instructions:
Heat the oil and ham fat over medium heat until fat has melted almost completely. Saute until almost crispy, (like bacon)Take out large pieces of ham and reserve.

Add onion, carrots, celery until slightly soft, about 4 minutes.

Add chopped cooked ham and potatoes, cook for 2 minutes, then add garlic, saute until fragrant (about 30 seconds)

Mix flour through mixture, cook for 2 minutes.

Chop the reserved pieces of "ham bacon", add to pan.

Stir in stock, mixing all ingredients together. Increase heat and bring to a boil until potatoes are just tender, (about 10 to 12 minutes).

Five years ago I got a call asking if there were wild flowers blooming at the Global Gardens farm stand. Yes, and they were exquisite in a drought year that left our local mountains bereft of their colorful gift. My friend said, “I’m sure you have heard of Amma Sri Karunamayi, you know the hugging saint”…No, I had never heard of her, even though she had millions of followers. “Well, she’s in the area and disappointed not to see CA wildflowers she was promised and I can’t be sure but I gave them your name and address”. I was busy. My daughter was in town visiting. I had promised her an afternoon at Avila Beach. We were packing up the car as I told my staff this “person” may be coming to check out the butterfly sanctuaries I had carefully planted around the property, aka California wildflowers. We were leaving when not one but three cars pulled in. (This meant our little parking lot was full.) Immediately from the cars nine men in long white robes emerged, carrying huge pots of steaming food, asking where they should go, they had brought a picnic lunch for “Amma” and they wanted to also “feed” us. From the third car emerged a gorgeous being, robed in pink and orange, seemingly emulating the wildflowers she was looking for. Amma was delighted as her assistant followed, helping her around. She saw I was leaving and said kindly, yet with great authority, “you must stay so I can feed you”. Anita and I looked at each other and parked our own car. I have to admit this was when I googled “Amma”. So we got out of the car. A beautiful luncheon, seemingly splayed before us in no time was ready. Amma insisted she give me the first fragrant bowl and that I sit down to eat. Anita was second. We felt like we were on Candid Camera or something. The afternoon unfolded and Amma asked if she could go inside our home which was on the same property as Global Gardens at that time. (Story continued in comments)

Chef Lisa’s Amazing 
Lima Bean Stew:
Ingredients
2 cups lima beans , dried
1 sweet onion , diced (about 3 inch diameter)
2 cloves garlic , finely chopped
1-2 tablespoons olive oil for sautéing , optional or use ⅓ cup broth for oil free
2 carrots , chopped (about 5 inches long)
2 stalks celery , chopped (about 8 inches long)
1 pound fresh spinach , chopped (or Swiss chard or both)
1 pound fresh tomatoes , diced
1 Zucchini diced
½ cup fresh parsley , chopped
1 Tbsp Global Gardens Greek Seasoning
Meyer Lemon Bliss Vinegar (1T per serving) 
Parmesan cheese (optional topping)
Instructions
Wash and soak the beans in a pot overnight.
The next day, drain the beans and add enough fresh water to cover them. Cook over low heat until half tender, about 30 minutes, drain, and save the broth.
Preheat oven to 350°F/180°C
In a large pot sauté the onions in veggie broth or olive oil for 2-3 minutes until they begins to get translucent. 
Add the garlic, carrots, celery, spinach and zucchini and sauté for a couple more minutes. 
Add beans and mix well.
Add tomatoes, salt and pepper and sauté for another minute. Then add parsley and mix well.
Add enough reserved broth from the beans to barely cover them. If you don’t have enough reserved broth, then use water for the rest (you can also use extra veggie broth).
Cook over medium heat for 15 minutes stirring, occasionally. Add more broth if needed. You don’t want it to get too dry.
Transfer to a 9 x 12 glass baking dish, cover and bake for 30 minutes, or until beans are tender and liquid has evaporated.
Uncover and bake for an additional 10 minutes.
Stir in Global Gardens Meyer Lemon Bliss Vinegar, and top with Parmesan cheese (optional)  Serve hot!

Mother’s Day Blueberry Olive Oil Cake 
1/2 cup brown sugar, packed
3/4 cup GG lemon infused olive oil
2 eggs
1  1/2 cup all-purpose flour
1 tsp baking powder
1 tsp baking soda
1/2 teaspoon sea salt
1/4 cup 2% milk
1 cup fresh blueberry

Streusel topping:

1/2 cup all-purpose fl
1/4 cup rolled oats
3 Tbsp coconut sugar
2 tsp grated lemon zest
3 Tbsp GG lemon infused olive oil

Preheat oven to 350°, grease  9” springform pan or flexible cake pan.

To make the cake, in a large mixing bowl, whisk brown sugar, olive oil and eggs until frothy.

Sift flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt over top of mixture, fold in with a wooden spoon or spatula to form a soft batter. Add milk and stir to combine, then fold in the blueberries.
PRO TIP: 
Lightly toss blueberries in a couple tablespoons of all-purpose flour before folding into batter. This keeps fruit from sinking to the bottom of your cake!

Pour the batter into prepared cake pan. Tap pan on the counter several times to ensure the batter is level and to remove any air bubbles.

To make the streusel topping, in a small bowl, combine the flower, oats, sugar, and zest. Drizzle in the olive oil and started combined into a coarse crumb mixture. Sprinkle this evenly over the cake batter. Bake the cake for 35 to 40 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Remove from oven, run a knife around the outside, and remove the sides of the pan let rest for at least 10 minutes before serving.

So you’re in the dog days of summer, got this season’s Classic Club trio and don’t know what to do with it? Fresh dinner in 15 minutes: 2T award-winning “Gold Standard” Taggiasca EVOO in a hot skillet, any fresh fish fillet (this is halibut), cook 10 min per inch, flip once for 1 minute, remove to serving dish with fresh organic cucumber, sweet onion and carrot, all sliced super thin, salted and drizzled with 2T Lime Chili Kick! Balsamic, 1T Bragg Aminos. Remove fish and lay over veggies. In hot skillet, keeping heat on, pour 1/4c Lime Chili Kick! into skillet, scraping up any browned bits with spatula, bring to boil and reduce 50%, about 5 minutes. Garnish with fresh basil and our Counterfeit Caviar (Theo’s recipe for Mustard Seed Charcuterie Spread you got with this shipment) Pour reduced vinegar over dish, go outside, enjoy the golden August light and EAT! How are YOU using this season’s Club trio? We have SO many more ideas for this season’s trio. Check our story and soon another recipe from Chef Jack from @cookingforlevi 🫶🏼

Recipe drop! Our amazing in-house Chef Lisa (follow her: @cheflisaolivesyou) has created a most flavorful, healthy, creatively wrapped granola bar for your weekend, in-store enjoyment at our Santa Ynez CA Provisions Store. Make these at home! 

Global Gardens Granola 
Goodness Bars

Ingredients:
2C  rolled oats
1/2C packed brown sugar
1/2C  dried apricots diced small
1/2C dried cranberries
1/2C unsalted whole roasted almonds (Chef Lisa used our Wonder Walnuts!) 
1/2C pumpkin seeds
½ t Global Gardens Holiday Hug Rub
½  t salt
1/2C smooth peanut butter or other nut butter
1/2C Global Gardens Hyper Local Tuscan EVOO
1/2C maple syrup
1/2C unsweetened coconut flakes
Few pinches flaky sea salt

Directions:
Preheat oven to 350°. Line 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper lightly brushed with olive oil.

Whisk nut butter, olive oil and maple syrup until smooth. Process 1/3C rolled oats into fine powder.  Add ground oats and all other ingredients, mixing completely into nut butter. 

Spread evenly in prepared pan pressing down firmly. Sprinkle lightly with sea salt. Bake 30 minutes, or until the top starts to brown and the edges are golden brown. Cool completely before cutting.

Ok so here’s a midweek quickie for you! The FOOD kind! Seriously the most surprisingly flavorful seafood dish we’ve ever made. Serves 2:
12oz halibut, sea bass or grouper fillet (if you’re lucky it will be from a local fisher person like our favorite @hahafishco)
12oz organic broccoli slaw
1/4c chopped sundried tomatoes
1/2c stemmed shitake shrooms
1 bunch scallions, chopped using the greens too
2T everything bagel seasoning 
4T Global Gardens Arbequina Extra Virgin Olive Oil
1t organic sesame oil 
2T Global Gardens Chili Lime Kick! Golden Balsamic Vinegar
Sauté shrooms, scallions and sundried tomatoes in 2T EVOO, not turning but allowing the mushroom caps to brown slightly. Brush 1/2T olive oil onto both sides of fish. Cost super well with seasoning. Add broccoli slaw to skillet mixture with 1T olive oil, two ounces of salt. Move veggies to circumference of pan encircling fish filet. Cook fish about 5 min per inch (skillet is already hot!) flipping about half way through. Veggies stay crunchy. Remove from skillet, arrange in serving bowl to retain juices. Drizzle fish only with 1t sesame oil and entire dish with 2T balsamic. This entire dish takes no more than 20 minutes including chop time! MERRY CHRISTMAS! We interrupt your scrolling to bring you this favorite holiday meal, our annual family tradition. A day to let go, wear PJ’s until it’s time to go to bed again and…eat joyously! Therefore no people photos as we’ve been posting a lot of those anyway but…here’s Theo’s best pot roast recipe:
Always use organic, hopefully local, hormone-free beef. Why? It tastes better and is better for our planet. 
This recipe is for a 3-lb beauty. Serves 6-8.

In a large Dutch oven, using your best Olio Nuovo brown 6 stalks chopped celery, one large shallot and 4 large minced garlic cloves. Add 1 cup Fig Balsamic and bring to a boil, scraping any burnt bits from bottom of pan. Next, on medium high heat place well-sea-salted, freshly-ground-pepper coated, Basil-Olive-Oiled roast on top of this mixture, turning only once on the bubbling vinegar and browned bits after about 3 minutes to throughly braise (brown). Remove browned roast from pan. Scrape more bits from bottom of pan. Add 1/2-1 bottle of Merlot or Cabernet wine to vinegar mixture, bringing back to a boil, reducing by about 50%~takes 10-12 minutes. Add one carton organic mushroom broth and stir well. Turn heat off. Place roast in pan. Scatter 1 1b assorted variety organic fingerling potatoes, 2 halved, seeded sweet peppers, 8-oz package baby bella mushrooms (which have all been tossed in 3T Basil olive oil, sea salt and freshly ground pepper) around and over roast. Add a few stalks of fresh sage, rosemary and thyme to top, do not stir these veggies or herb stalks in, just simply layer them, completing layering with herb stalks on top.) Place lidded Dutch oven into a 275° oven for 2 1/2 hours. Serve over your best egg noodles! Make sandwiches with any leftovers using all the veggies on the sandos too. 💚❤️Memorable! #familytime #roast #recipe #oliveoil #foodie #christmasdinner #tradition
